<topic id="b7e96cd7-c737-4805-b5a9-98f1e8acd1d5" revisionNumber="1">
    <developerConceptualDocument xmlns="http://ddue.schemas.microsoft.com/authoring/2003/5" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink">

        <introduction>
            <para>
                DigitalRise Graphics supports different anti-aliasing methods.
            </para>
            <autoOutline/>
        </introduction>


        <section address="MSAA">
            <title>Multisample Anti-Aliasing (MSAA)</title>
            <content>
                <para>
                    <newTerm>Multisample Anti-Aliasing</newTerm> (MSAA) is supported by the XNA Framework:
                    See
                    <externalLink>
                        <linkText>MSDN: Enabling Antialiasing (Multisampling)</linkText>
                        <linkUri>http://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/bb975403.aspx</linkUri>
                    </externalLink>.
                </para>
                <para>
                    However, MSAA is not compatible with the light pre-pass renderer ("deferred lighting")
                    as implemented in the examples. It is recommended to use
                    <newTerm>Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing</newTerm> (FXAA) or
                    <newTerm>Enhanced Subpixel Morphological Anti-Aliasing</newTerm> (SMAA) instead.
                </para>
            </content>
        </section>


        <section address="FXAA">
            <title>Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing (FXAA)</title>
            <content>
                <para>
                    <newTerm>Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing</newTerm> (FXAA) is implemented as a
                    post-process filter. See
                    <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DigitalRise.Graphics.PostProcessing.FxaaFilter</codeEntityReference>.
                </para>
            </content>
        </section>


        <section address="SMAA">
            <title>Enhanced Subpixel Morphological Anti-Aliasing (SMAA)</title>
            <content>
                <para>
                    <newTerm>Enhanced Subpixel Morphological Anti-Aliasing</newTerm> (SMAA) is implemented as
                    a post-process filter. See
                    <codeEntityReference qualifyHint="false">T:DigitalRise.Graphics.PostProcessing.SmaaFilter</codeEntityReference>.
                </para>
            </content>
        </section>


